ndleCondense`.\\n\\nThe fundamental issue is that a session should only be condensed when the commit actually contains files the session modified and the content matches what that session wrote. The architecture breaks down because `sessionHasNewContent` looks at a shared shadow branch — if one session has new content there, it returns true for all sessions sharing that branch, even if they didn't contribute to those changes.\\n\\nFor IDLE sessions that were previously condensed, the `CheckpointTranscriptStart` should track whether the transcript has grown since the last condensation, but I'm seeing cases where sessions report `has_new: true` despite having zero checkpoints. I need to trace through the logic more carefully — particularly whether carry-forward condensations are properly updating the checkpoint markers, or if the live transcript fallback is incorrectly triggering for sessions that shouldn't have new content. into other checkpoints\\n\\nFor IDLE session going through `HandleCondense`:\\n1. `sessionHasNewContent` is called\\n2. Shadow branch exists (shared with other sessions)\\n3. Looks for transcript at `.entire/metadata/37a27d31.../full.jsonl` on shadow branch\\n4. If it finds it (from a previous condensation that put it there?), no — condensation writes to `entire/checkpoints/v1`, not the shadow branch\\n5. If it doesn't find it, `hasTranscriptFile = false`\\n6. Checks `state.FilesTouched` — if carry-forward set this, it could be non-empty\\n7. If non-empty, at line 949-950: \\\"PostCommit context: no staged files, but we have carry-forward files. Return true\\\"\\n\\nThat's the key issue for IDLE sessions. The code returns true whenever `FilesTouched` is populated, delegating the overlap check to the caller, but HandleCondense only performs that check for non-ACTIVE sessions and even then might skip it due to the parent tree shortcut. With the fix in place, HandleCondense now properly intersects with the committed file set and validates content overlap, so IDLE sessions should be filtered correctly.\\n\\nBut ENDED sessions are handled differently — they go through `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched`, which skips the overlap check entirely. The real issue is that `sessionHasNewContent` and `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` don't actually verify whether the files being committed overlap with the session's files. I need to unify the overlap check so both functions use the same logic to intersect the session files with the committed files, preventing the carry-forward cycle from perpetuating.\\n\\nThe deeper problem is that \\\"new content\\\" for condensation purposes should mean either the transcript has grown since the last condensation or the session has files overlapping with the current commit — but right now carry-forward files are being treated as new content even when they're just leftover files that weren't included in the commit.\\n\\nSo the real fix is to make `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` check for overlap with the committed files, and then `sessionHasNewContent` should only return true when there's actual transcript growth or relevant file overlap.\\n\\nI'm weighing two approaches: either add the overlap check to both handlers separately, or consolidate them into a single handler that does the overlap check once before any condensation happens. The consolidated approach feels cleaner architecturally since it eliminates the duplication.\\n\\nThe real issue is that `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` relies on `sessionHasNewContent` to determine whether to condense, but that function is returning true whenever files are touched even if there's no actual transcript growth—I need to tighten that logic so it only returns true when there's genuinely new content worth condensing. And `sessionHasNewContent` at line 949-950 returns `true` when `FilesTouched` is non-empty (carry-forward files) even though there's no transcript on the shadow branch and no transcript growth.\\n\\nSo there are two layers of bug:\\n1. `sessionHasNewContent` returning true based on carry-forward files alone (no actual new content)\\n2. `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` not checking overlap with committed files\\n\\nIf we fix #2 (add overlap check), then #1 becomes less harmful but still causes unnecessary work (extracting session data, etc.). We could fix both.\\n\\nBut actually, I think fixing #1 might break legitimate carry-forward scenarios. Imagine:\\n- Session writes file A and B\\n- User commits file A → condensation + carry-forward for file B\\n- Shadow branch is deleted (condensation deletes it)\\n- User commits file B →\\n\\nWe want condensation to apply here. When `sessionHasNewContent` is called, there's no shadow branch and no transcript, but `FilesTouched = [B]`. If we return false, file B's commit won't get the session data. So `sessionHasNewContent` returning true for carry-forward files is actually correct—it's signaling that there's data needing association with commits touching those files. The real issue is that the caller doesn't verify the committed files actually overlap with what we're condensing.\\n\\nThe fix is straightforward: apply the committed-files overlap check in `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` the same way it's done in `HandleCondense`. There's also an important insight about how the overlap check in `HandleCondense` works that's relevant here. fixed)\\n\\nSo the remaining gap is `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched`. The real issue is that carry-forward creates a self-perpetuating cycle — each condensation triggers carry-forward, which sets `FilesTouched`, making the session appear to have new content, which feeds into the next condensation. Even with an overlap check, ENDED sessions stay at their old BaseCommit with accumulated `FilesTouched`, ready to trigger again on the next commit.\\n\\nThe fix is to apply the same overlap logic to `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched`. But there's a timing subtlety: `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` checks the current `FilesTouched` value, while `HandleCondense` checks the value from before the transition. For ENDED sessions where the transition doesn't modify `FilesTouched`, these should match, but I need to verify the action dispatch order — `ActionCondenseIfFilesTouched` and `ActionUpdateLastInteraction` are dispatched after the transition, and neither modifies `FilesTouched` beforehand.\\n\\nSo the real issue is twofold: first, apply the overlap check to protect ENDED sessions 3 and 4 from condensing on carry-forward files alone, and second, fix `sessionHasNewContent` so it doesn't return true just because `FilesTouched` is non-empty when there's no transcript on the shadow branch.\\n\\nBut actually, there's a deeper problem here. Even if `sessionHasNewContent` returns true for carry-forward files and the handler's overlap check rejects it, we're still doing unnecessary work extracting session data just to throw it away. The real culprit is that carry-forward keeps `FilesTouched` populated even after condensation, because `filesWithRemainingAgentChanges` checks if uncommitted files still match agent content.\\n\\nLet me trace through the log to understand what's happening...\\n\\nAfter condensing session 0, carry-forward found that `manual_commit_test.go` wasn't committed and kept it in `FilesTouched`. This perpetuates the cycle. With the overlap check in place, even though `FilesTouched` has files, if those files don't overlap with the committed files, the session won't condense—so the condensation cycle is broken, but `FilesTouched` keeps accumulating.\\n\\nThe real issue is whether old ended sessions should just sit around forever with carry-forward files, getting checked on every commit. That's not great for performance, but it's correct. The better question is whether old ended sessions should eventually be cleaned up—like, if a session hasn't been condensed in N commits, should we stop checking it?\\n\\nThat's a design question for the user though. For now, the immediate fix is applying the overlap check to `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched`. The core problem is that all three condensation handlers weren't sufficiently checking whether committed files actually overlap with the session's files. The proper fix is applying the overlap check to all condensation paths.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":406,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":122322,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":406},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYGo85WoSwogJPfiSVs1m\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"5464c9e4-3ab1-4185-a853-1e797e230520\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T04:29:20.746Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"5464c9e4-3ab1-4185-a853-1e797e230520\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2\",\"sessionId\":\"d54f5fdd-71a4-43e3-a8cf-ee0722e84c19\",\"version\":\"2.1.45\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/fix-multi-session-vacuums-too-much\",\"slug\":\"witty-petting-dream\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01BBgP7BwyRMDrNmHRrMZoHt\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The logs tell the full story. Let me lay out what's actually happening:\\n\\n**The sessions and their phases at condensation time:**\\n\\n| Session | Phase | Handler | Why condensed? |\\n|---------|-------|---------|---------------|\\n| 0 (PR review) | **ENDED** | `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` | `files_touched=1, has_new=true` |\\n| 1 (merge conflicts) | **IDLE** | `HandleCondense` | `has_new=true` |\\n| 2 (PR review) | **IDLE** | `HandleCondense` | `has_new=true` |\\n| 3 (logging plan) | **ENDED** | `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` | `files_touched=1, has_new=true` |\\n| 4 (PR review) | **ENDED** | `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` | `files_touched=2, has_new=true` |\\n| 5 (PR review) | **ENDED** | `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` | (same pattern) |\\n| 6 (PR review) | **ACTIVE** | `HandleCondense` | `has_new=true` (the actual working session) |\\n\\nSo it's not stale ACTIVE sessions at all. It's mostly **ENDED sessions** going through `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched`, which has **zero overlap checking** — it just checks `len(state.FilesTouched) > 0 && h.hasNew`.\\n\\n**The self-perpetuating cycle:**\\n\\n1. Session finishes (ENDED), gets condensed on first commit — carry-forward sets `FilesTouched` with uncommitted files\\n2. Next commit: `sessionHasNewContent` returns `true` because `FilesTouched` is non-empty (line 949-950) → `hasNew = true`\\n3. `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` sees `FilesTouched > 0 && hasNew` → condenses again\\n4. Carry-forward recalculates remaining files → sets `FilesTouched` again\\n5. Goto 2, forever\\n\\nThe PR we just shipped only fixes `HandleCondense` (IDLE/ACTIVE path). The ENDED path through `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched` is completely unguarded. That's where most of these sessions went.\\n\\n**The proper fix is to apply the same overlap check to `HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched`:**\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (h *postCommitActionHandler) HandleCondenseIfFilesTouched(state *session.State) error {\\n    shouldCondense := len(state.FilesTouched) > 0 && h.hasNew\\n    if shouldCondense && len(h.filesTouchedBefore) > 0 {\\n        var committedTouchedFiles []string\\n        for _, f := range h.filesTouchedBefore {\\n            if _, ok := h.committedFileSet[f]; ok {\\n                committedTouchedFiles = append(committedTouchedFiles, f)\\n            }\\n        }\\n        if len(committedTouchedFiles) > 0 {\\n            shouldCondense = filesOverlapWithContent(h.repo, h.shadowBranchName, h.commit, committedTouchedFiles)\\n        } else {\\n            shouldCondense = false\\n        }\\n    }\\n    // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis way ALL condensation paths — ACTIVE, IDLE, and ENDED — verify that committed files actually overlap with session files before condensing. The carry-forward cycle breaks because unrelated commits no longer trigger condensation.\\n\\nWant me to implement this and update the PR?\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":406,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":122322,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":406},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYGo85WoSwogJPfiSVs1m\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"2339eeaa-05bc-4a19-9fea-001976385818\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T04:29:33.401Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"2339eeaa-05bc-4a19-9fea-001976385818\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2\",\"sessionId\":\"d54f5fdd-71a4-43e3-a8cf-ee0722e84c19\",\"version\":\"2.1.45\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/fix-multi-session-vacuums-too-much\",\"slug\":\"witty-petting-dream\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"Stop\",\"hookName\":\"Stop\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"708ce5ff-5014-4ba7-9bbd-2f5fda438d85\",\"toolUseID\":\"708ce5ff-5014-4ba7-9bbd-2f5fda438d85\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T04:29:33.505Z\",\"uuid\":\"acb12c40-a347-47cf-8234-076ae9def356\"}\n{\"type\":\"queue-operation\",\"operation\":\"dequeue\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T04:29:33.868Z\",\"sessionId\":\"d54f5fdd-71a4-43e3-a8cf-ee0722e84c19\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"acb12c40-a347-47cf-8234-076ae9def356\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2\",\"sessionId\":\"d54f5fdd-71a4-43e3-a8cf-ee0722e84c19\",\"version\":\"2.1.45\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/fix-multi-session-vacuums-too-much\",\"slug\":\"witty-petting-dream\",\"type\":\"system\",\"subtype\":\"stop_hook_summary\",\"hookCount\":1,\"hookInfos\":[{\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code sto